For the not unusual medieval view that Caesar was the first
emperor, see ^Convivio~ IV.v.12.  For the Suetonian source of his
falcon-like eyes see Campi (comm. to ^Inf~. IV.123).  That Caesar is
here in armor may well be a reminder of his crossing of the Rubicon in
arms to attack Rome (see William Stull and Robert Hollander, "The
Lucanian Source of Dante's Ulysses," ^Studi Danteschi~ 63 [1991
(1997)], p. 36).  (Pertile wonders at the reasons for Caesar's being in
arms -- "Il nobile castello, il paradiso terrestre e l'umanesimo
dantesco," ^Filologia e critica~ 5 [1980], p. 17.)
